 and Jacob (Genesis 24–27). The Hebrew root occurs in the Bible only in the vocabulary word <i>marbek</i> ‘cattle stall’, and its connection with the name is doubtful. In any case, Rebecca was Aramean, and the name probably has a source in Aramaic. It has always been common as a Jewish name; in England and elsewhere it began to be used also by Christians from the 14th century onwards and especially at the time of the Reformation, when Old Testament names became popular. It was very common among the Puritans in the 17th century, and has enjoyed a tremendous vogue in England since the latter part of the 20th century, among people of many different creeds. In Scotland this is found as an Anglicized form of Beathag ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Eva Rebecca Gorn was born in 1400, in Wrotham, Kent, England, United Kingdom, her father, George K Gorn, was 25 and her mother, Fanny, was 24. She married Lord John Nisell I in 1419, in England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son. She died in 1451, in her hometown, at the age of 51."},"et":{"1400–1451":"1400–1451","1394–1424":"1394–1424","1417–1451":"1417–1451","1376–Male":"1376–Surnud","1376–Female":"1376–Surnud","1424":"1424","before 1400":"enne 1400","1400":"1400","1376":"1376","1451":"1451","1394":"1394","1419":"1419","1417":"1417","Wrotham, Kent, England, United Kingdom":"Wrotham, Kent, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Wrotham, Kent, England":"Wrotham, Kent, England","England":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1400–1451":"1400–1451","1394–1424":"1394–1424","1417–1451":"1417–1451","1376–Male":"1376–Kuollut","1376–Female":"1376–Kuollut","1424":"1424","before 1400":"ennen vuotta 1400","1400":"1400","1376":"1376","1451":"1451","1394":"1394","1419":"1419","1417":"1417","Wrotham, Kent, England, United Kingdom":"Wrotham, Kent, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Wrotham, Kent, England":"Wrotham, Kent, England","England":"Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"1400–1451":"1400–1451","1394–1424":"139